## Diagnosis

The bug is in `Navigation.module.scss`. The `.logo` flex item has `flex-shrink: 0` and `.logoText` has `white-space: nowrap` — both correct in isolation — but the **`.navInner`** flex row is missing the `overflow: hidden` / `min-width: 0` isolation on `.links` that forces all compression to go rightward. More critically, `.logo` is only declared `flex-shrink: 0`, not `flex: none`. The difference matters: `flex-shrink: 0` still participates in the flex sizing algorithm and the browser *can* still wrap the logo text in extreme squeeze scenarios because the shorthand `flex` also sets `flex-basis: auto`, which doesn't clamp. The `.links` side also lacks `overflow: hidden` to contain the tagline's wrapping within its own box.

## Root Cause

**AP-066 — Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text.** The existing fix attempt (`flex-shrink: 0` on `.logo`, `min-width: 0` on `.links`) is incomplete. The canonical fix requires `flex: none` (which expands to `flex: 0 0 auto` — no grow, no shrink, auto basis) on the protected item, plus `overflow: hidden` on the yielding sibling so the browser has no ambiguity about where to absorb the overflow budget.

---

## Fix

### 1. `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`

```scss
@use '../../../styles' as *;

.nav {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: var(--portfolio-z-sticky);
  background-color: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-subtle);
  box-shadow: 0 4px 12px -4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);

  &::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    bottom: 0;
    left: 0;
    right: 0;
    height: 10px;
    transform: translateY(100%);
    backdrop-filter: blur(3px);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(3px);
    mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2), transparent);
    -webkit-mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2), transparent);
    pointer-events: none;
  }
}

.navInner {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: space-between;
  max-width: $elan-container-wide;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-2x);

  @media #{$elan-mq-sm} {
    padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-4x);
  }
}

.logo {
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: $portfolio-spacer-0-5x;
  text-decoration: none;
  // ─── Identity Lock (AP-066) ───────────────────────────────────────────────
  // The logo is the site's primary identity line. It MUST NEVER wrap or shrink
  // under any flex pressure at any viewport width. This is a hard design
  // principle, not a convenience — see AP-066 and navigation.md §4.7.
  //
  // `flex: none` expands to `flex: 0 0 auto`: no grow, no shrink, natural
  // content width as basis. This is stronger than `flex-shrink: 0` alone,
  // which still allows the flex algorithm to compress the item when the
  // container's free space is negative.
  flex: none;
  @include transition-fast;

  &:hover {
    .logoMark {
      background-color: var(--portfolio-text-neutral-max);
    }

    .logoText {
      color: var(--portfolio-text-neutral-max);
    }
  }
}

.logoMark {
  display: inline-block;
  height: calc($portfolio-type-2xl * 1.2);
  aspect-ratio: 1;
  flex-shrink: 0;
  background-color: $portfolio-accent-60;
  mask-image: url('/images/yg-logo.svg');
  mask-size: contain;
  mask-repeat: no-repeat;
  @include transition-fast;
}

.logoText {
  font-family: $portfolio-font-serif;
  font-size: $portfolio-type-2xl;
  font-weight: $portfolio-weight-regular;
  line-height: $portfolio-leading-snug;
  color: $portfolio-accent-60;
  letter-spacing: $portfolio-tracking-tight;
  white-space: nowrap;
  @include transition-fast;
}

.links {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: var(--portfolio-spacer-3x);
  // ─── Soft Edge (AP-066) ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
  // The links/tagline region is the flex row's yield zone. `min-width: 0`
  // allows this item to shrink below its intrinsic content size so its
  // children (tagline) can wrap without the logo ever being touched.
  // `overflow: hidden` is also required — without it the browser still
  // allocates width to overflowing text, which leaks back into the logo
  // item's budget indirectly.
  min-width: 0;
  overflow: hidden;
}

.link {
  font-family: var(--portfolio-font-sans);
  font-size: var(--portfolio-type-sm);
  font-weight: var(--portfolio-weight-regular);
  color: var(--portfolio-text-secondary);
  text-decoration: none;
  @include transition-fast;

  &:hover {
    color: var(--portfolio-text-primary);
  }
}

.linkActive {
  color: var(--portfolio-text-primary);
  font-weight: var(--portfolio-weight-medium);
}

.tagline {
  @include body-sm;
  color: var(--portfolio-text-secondary);
  // The tagline is the nav's intentional soft edge: it wraps freely under
  // viewport squeeze. Two-line cap prevents it from invading site content.
  min-width: 0;
  text-align: right;
  display: -webkit-box;
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
  -webkit-line-clamp: 2;
  line-clamp: 2;
  overflow: hidden;
}
```

### 2. `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — amend AP-066

Locate the existing AP-066 block and replace it with the strengthened version:

```markdown
<a id="ap-066"></a>
## AP-066: Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text

**Status: ACTIVE**
**Last amended:** 2026-04-27 (FB-146: strengthened fix to `flex: none`; added Identity Priority Rule and `overflow: hidden` requirement on yielding sibling.)

**Trigger:** A nav or header flex row contains a site logo/name alongside secondary content (tagline, links). Under viewport squeeze, the logo text wraps to two lines even though `white-space: nowrap` and `flex-shrink: 0` are present.

**Why it's wrong:** `flex-shrink: 0` alone is not sufficient. It prevents the flex algorithm from *explicitly* shrinking the item, but when the container's free space is negative (i.e., children are collectively wider than the row), the browser can still compress items if no item is declared `flex: none`. The `flex` shorthand also sets `flex-basis: auto`, which tells the browser the item's natural size — but without the explicit `0` shrink factor locked via the shorthand form, extreme squeeze can still corrupt the layout. The absence of `overflow: hidden` on the yielding sibling also leaves the browser's width-budget accounting ambiguous: overflowing text from the tagline can leak back into the logo's allocated space.

**Identity Priority Rule (navigation-specific):**
> **Logo and site name lines are the hard edge. Secondary nav content (taglines, role blurbs, nav links) is the soft edge.** Under any amount of viewport pressure, the hard edge must never compromise — not wrapping, not truncating, not shifting to a second line. The soft edge absorbs all overflow by wrapping onto additional lines. This is a design principle, not an implementation preference.

**Correct alternative — the full three-part pattern:**

```css
/* 1. The identity item: completely rigid */
.logo {
  flex: none;           /* = flex: 0 0 auto — no grow, no shrink, natural width */
  white-space: nowrap;  /* belt + suspenders: also on inner text span */
}

/* 2. The yielding item: explicitly opt into compression */
.links {
  min-width: 0;         /* allows flex item to shrink below intrinsic size */
  overflow: hidden;     /* prevents overflowing children from leaking width budget */
}

/* 3. The soft content: clamp gracefully */
.tagline {
  min-width: 0;
  display: -webkit-box;
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
  -webkit-line-clamp: 2;
  overflow: hidden;
}
```

**Why `flex: none` and not `flex-shrink: 0`:** `flex: none` is the shorthand that sets `flex: 0 0 auto` — zero grow, zero shrink, auto basis. `flex-shrink: 0` only overrides the shrink factor; the flex-basis remains whatever the element's natural size is, and in a severely constrained row the browser's sizing algorithm can still produce unexpected compression on auto-basis items. `flex: none` is unambiguous: the item takes exactly its content width, always.

**See:** FB-146 (nav logo "Yilan Gao" wrapping under squeeze), FB-150 (experience column company names wrapping).
```

### 3. `docs/design/navigation.md` — add §4.7 Identity Priority Rule

Add the following section directly after §4.6's existing content (after the hover-to-reveal sliver section):

```markdown
### 4.7 Identity Priority Rule — Logo and Site Name

**Source:** Session 2026-04-27, FB-146. See AP-066.

**The rule:** The site name ("Yilan Gao") and its logo mark are the nav's **hard edge**. They must never wrap, truncate, compress, or move to a second line under any viewport pressure. This is a non-negotiable branding principle — a two-line logo is a broken logo, not a responsive adaptation.

Secondary nav content — taglines, role blurbs, contextual links — is the **soft edge**. It absorbs all viewport pressure by wrapping gracefully.

**Implementation contract for any nav row containing an identity mark:**

| Element | CSS | Why |
|---------|-----|-----|
| Logo / site name container | `flex: none` | Locks out of flex sizing algorithm entirely — zero grow, zero shrink, natural width always. Stronger than `flex-shrink: 0`. |
| Inner text span | `white-space: nowrap` | Belt-and-suspenders: prevents the span from breaking even if flex container math somehow allows compression. |
| Yielding sibling (tagline, links) | `min-width: 0; overflow: hidden` | Explicitly opts into compression. Without `overflow: hidden`, overflowing text leaks width budget back into the logo's space. |
| Soft content (tagline text) | `-webkit-line-clamp: 2; overflow: hidden` | Bounds the soft wrapping to two lines — prevents nav from growing to infinite height. |

**Anti-pattern to avoid:** Using only `flex-shrink: 0` on the logo. This is insufficient — it prevents explicit shrinking but does not protect the item when the container's total free space goes negative. Use `flex: none`.
```

---

## Principle

This is **AP-066 — Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text**, now strengthened with the explicit **Identity Priority Rule**: logo and site name are the *hard edge* of any nav row; secondary content is the *soft edge*. All viewport pressure routes through the soft edge only. The mechanical guarantee requires three cooperating declarations — `flex: none` on the hard edge, `min-width: 0; overflow: hidden` on the soft edge, and `-webkit-line-clamp` on the text within it. Any one of the three missing breaks the guarantee: `flex: none` without `overflow: hidden` on the sibling still allows width budget leakage; `overflow: hidden` without `min-width: 0` still prevents the sibling from shrinking below its intrinsic size; and neither helps if the inner text has no line-clamp to bound the nav's height growth. The fix is only complete when all three are in place simultaneously.
